{{nihongo|'''Otohiko Ichiki'''|市来 乙彦|Ichiki Otohiko|May 7, 1872 &ndash; February 19, 1954}} was a [[Japanese people|Japanese]] businessman, central banker and the 10th Governor of the [[Bank of Japan]] (BOJ).

==Early life==
Ichiki was born in [[Kagoshima Prefecture]].<ref>Bank of Japan (BOJ), [http://www.boj.or.jp/en/about/outline/history/pre_gov/sousai10.htm/ 10th Governor]</ref>  

==Career==
In 1922-1923, Ichiki was briefly Finance Minister in the cabinet of [[Katō Tomosaburō]].<ref>Metzler, Mark. (2006). {{Google books|NRHlkwQ0JH4C|''Lever of Empire: the International Gold Standard and the Crisis of Liberalism in Prewar Japan,'' p. 141.|page=141}}</ref>  As head of the [[Ministry of Finance (Japan)|Ministry of Finance]], he was cautious in response to unsettled financial situation.<ref>James, Harold ''et al.'' (2002). {{Google books|hHDylbrKDwMC|The Role of Banks in the Interwar Economy,'' p. 254.|page=254}}</ref>  Ichiki was Governor of the Bank of Japan from September 5, 1923 through May 10, 1927.<ref>BOJ, [http://www.boj.or.jp/en/about/outline/history/pre_gov/index.htm/ List of Governors].</ref>

