{{use dmy dates|date=October 2018}} {{Infobox criminal |image = |birth_name = |birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1977|02|14}} |birth_place = Singapore |death_date = |death_place = |death_cause = |occupation = {{unbulleted list|Director of Wee Tiong|Managing director of WT Marine}} |net_worth = |spouse = |children = |conviction = |image_caption = |alias = {{unbulleted list|"WB"|Marcus Tan}} |conviction_penalty = }}
'''Tan Wee Beng''' (born 14 February 1977) is a Singaporean businessman and [[commodity broker]] currently on a [[most wanted list]] maintained by the United States [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI)]] for [[money laundering]].
==Career== ===Business=== A graduate of [[Nanyang Technological University, Singapore]], Tan serves as the director of Wee Tiong and the managing director of WT Marine. In 2011, he was named the Emerging Entrepreneur of the Year by [[Ernst & Young]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ey.com/sg/en/about-us/entrepreneurship/entrepreneur-of-the-year/eoy_2011_winner_emerging|title=EY Entrepreneur Of The Year 2011 – Emerging|publisher=Ersnt & Young|accessdate=26 October 2018}}</ref> Under his leadership, annual revenue at Wee Tiong reportedly grew by some 131 percent in ten years to more than [[United States dollar|USD$]]300m in 2015.<ref name=bbc>{{cite news|newspaper=BBC|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-45987533|title=Singapore trader denies laundering millions for North Korea|date=26 October 2018}}</ref>
===Alleged money laundering=== On 25 October 2018, the [[United States Department of Justice]] officially filed charges against Tan for his "conspiring to use the U.S. financial system to conduct millions of dollars’ worth of transactions to finance shipments of goods to the [[Democratic People’s Republic of Korea]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.justice.gov/usao-sdny/pr/manhattan-united-states-attorney-announces-charges-against-owner-and-director-singapore|title=Manhattan United States Attorney Announces Charges Against Owner And Director Of Singapore-Based Commodities Company For North Korea Sanctions Evasion And Money Laundering Offenses|date=25 October 2018|publisher=United States Department of Justice|accessdate=26 October 2018}}</ref> At the same time, the [[United States Department of the Treasury]] announced sanctions against Tan and the two companies under his leadership.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://home.treasury.gov/news/press-releases/sm533|title=Treasury Designates Singapore-Based Targets for Laundering Money in Support of North Korea|date=25 October 2018|publisher=United States Department of the Treasury|accessdate=26 October 2018}}</ref> Tan categorically denied the criminal allegations.<ref name=bbc/>
==Personal life== The ''[[South China Morning Post]]'' described Tan as a "Ferrari-loving entrepreneur" based on his alleged penchant for [[sports car]]s.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=South China Morning Post|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/southeast-asia/article/2170263/fbi-indicts-singapores-tan-wee-beng-ferrari-loving|title=FBI indicts Singapore’s Tan Wee Beng, Ferrari-loving entrepreneur, for laundering North Korea funds|date=25 October 2017}}</ref> According to his ''Business Times'' profile, Tan is also a member of the London-based Refined Sugar Association.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Wee Tiong|url=http://www.weetiong.com.sg/press-article-3.php|title=Keeping the middleman relevant in the Net age|accessdate=26 October 2018}}</ref>
